A Russian software engineer, Eugene Roshal, launched WinRAR in 1995 with a 40-day free trial. But here’s the twist—it never truly stopped working. Even after the trial expired, the software remained fully usable, with no lockouts or forced payments—just a small reminder asking users to purchase a license. Most people ignored the message and continued using it. 

Over time, millions kept running the “trial” version. This wasn’t a planned “permanent free trial” strategy, but rather a simple and lenient shareware model. While many individuals use it for free, businesses and organizations still pay for licenses, which sustains the software. This approach helped WinRAR spread globally and remain relevant for decades.

